And incidentally, the main
idea of the "Incerto--"

00:12:15.030 --> 00:12:18.890
the "Incerto" if one
asked to describe it,

00:12:18.890 --> 00:12:23.320
I say it's a series of fables--

00:12:23.320 --> 00:12:26.130
what do I call it?

00:12:26.130 --> 00:12:29.190
An investigation of opacity,
luck, uncertainty, probability,

00:12:29.190 --> 00:12:33.410
lalala in a form
of personal essays

00:12:33.410 --> 00:12:36.110
with autobiographical
sections, stories, parable,

00:12:36.110 --> 00:12:38.510
philosophical, historical,
and scientific discussion.

00:12:38.510 --> 00:12:41.510
So basically, it's a mishmash
of things that turn out

00:12:41.510 --> 00:12:43.242
to be reasonable for some.

00:12:43.242 --> 00:12:47.700
Or at least they pay the price,
whether they read it or not,

00:12:47.700 --> 00:12:48.755
it's not--

00:12:48.755 --> 00:12:50.180
I get the same.

00:12:50.180 --> 00:12:52.710
The money doesn't change.

00:12:52.710 --> 00:12:55.550
But there is one point about
the "Incerto," pervading

00:12:55.550 --> 00:13:00.450
the "Incerto," and I realized
too late to put it in the book,

00:13:00.450 --> 00:13:02.750
that there's a lot of
uncertainty in the world.

00:13:02.750 --> 00:13:05.780
There's a lot more uncertainty
than you think there is.

00:13:05.780 --> 00:13:10.630
But the way to deal with
such uncertainty is unique.

00:13:10.630 --> 00:13:12.020
So in other words,
there is a lot

00:13:12.020 --> 00:13:15.050
of certainty about how
to act under conditions

00:13:15.050 --> 00:13:17.430
of uncertainty.

00:13:17.430 --> 00:13:20.100
A very simple example.

00:13:20.100 --> 00:13:22.670
If you receive from Ar Raqqa--

00:13:22.670 --> 00:13:23.810
which is in Syria--

00:13:23.810 --> 00:13:28.320
and ISIS, an ISIS thing, a
package, and written on it,

00:13:28.320 --> 00:13:29.360
originates in Ar Raqqa.

00:13:29.360 --> 00:13:31.202
This is a package.

00:13:31.202 --> 00:13:32.160
What do you do with it?

00:13:32.160 --> 00:13:33.411
Do you open it?

00:13:33.411 --> 00:13:33.910
No.

00:13:33.910 --> 00:13:36.800
So you have a lot of certainty
what to do with that package.

00:13:36.800 --> 00:13:40.340
So the more uncertainty
there is, the more certainty

00:13:40.340 --> 00:13:41.870
there is in what to do.

00:13:41.870 --> 00:13:44.790
If you really don't know
if the plane is robust,

00:13:44.790 --> 00:13:46.730
you don't get on it.

00:13:46.730 --> 00:13:49.160
So the more uncertainty
about the plane,

00:13:49.160 --> 00:13:53.090
the more certainty
about not getting on it.

00:13:53.090 --> 00:13:56.690
And this is sort of what
permeates the "Incerto,"

00:13:56.690 --> 00:13:58.359
but I couldn't put
it in concise terms,

00:13:58.359 --> 00:13:59.400
because it takes a while.

00:13:59.400 --> 00:14:04.130
It takes me 25 years to bring
an idea to its summary, you see?

00:14:04.130 --> 00:14:07.700
So maybe if you invite me
to give another talk here,

00:14:07.700 --> 00:14:11.710
in five years I'll be
explaining "Skin in the Game."

00:14:11.710 --> 00:14:15.200
So now, simple application of
"Skin in the Game" to make you

00:14:15.200 --> 00:14:20.525
really realize what's going on
with our knowledge of the world

00:14:20.525 --> 00:14:21.650
without "Skin in the Game."

00:14:21.650 --> 00:14:24.870
Haven't explained yet
"Skin in the Game."

00:14:24.870 --> 00:14:28.710
This is commonly
known as a restaurant.

00:14:28.710 --> 00:14:30.740
A friend of mine,
who like me was

00:14:30.740 --> 00:14:32.660
a trader-- he was a
former partner at Goldman

00:14:32.660 --> 00:14:36.200
Sachs, an oil trader, so
he talks like oil traders--

00:14:36.200 --> 00:14:39.050
had gotten a very
bad idea to invest

00:14:39.050 --> 00:14:40.100
in a restaurant business.

00:14:40.100 --> 00:14:42.350
And if I have one piece of
advice, in case I die here,

00:14:42.350 --> 00:14:44.270
just don't invest in
the restaurant business.

00:14:44.270 --> 00:14:48.640
Don't open a restaurant
unless you really

00:14:48.640 --> 00:14:52.142
want to lose your money
slowly, or sometimes quickly

00:14:52.142 --> 00:14:52.850
in New York City.

00:14:52.850 --> 00:14:58.760
So he discovered the following,
that the restaurant business

00:14:58.760 --> 00:15:02.360
has a lot of prizes.

00:15:02.360 --> 00:15:05.300
The best sushi in
lower Manhattan,

00:15:05.300 --> 00:15:10.110
the best sushi with music,
best sushi without-- whatever.

00:15:10.110 --> 00:15:12.200
So we have all these
categories, OK?

00:15:12.200 --> 00:15:14.650
And then there is a best
restaurant in that category.

00:15:14.650 --> 00:15:19.850
The best rare steak, the best
T-bone west of the Hudson,

00:15:19.850 --> 00:15:21.590
you have all these categories.

00:15:21.590 --> 00:15:23.540
And they're prizes, actually.

00:15:23.540 --> 00:15:26.960
Now who decides on these prizes?

00:15:26.960 --> 00:15:30.170
Journalists and other
restaurant owners.

00:15:30.170 --> 00:15:33.560
There is a gala dinner where
they give these prizes.

00:15:33.560 --> 00:15:35.910
And guess what?

00:15:35.910 --> 00:15:41.520
Most restaurants who got prizes
were closed, were shut down,

00:15:41.520 --> 00:15:44.370
were shut down out of business.

00:15:44.370 --> 00:15:48.510
So it tells you the
following, any business

00:15:48.510 --> 00:15:50.460
where you're judged
by your peers

00:15:50.460 --> 00:15:54.680
and not by some
contact with reality

00:15:54.680 --> 00:15:57.450
is going to rot eventually.

00:15:57.450 --> 00:16:00.180
That's why companies go
bust, this is what happens.

00:16:00.180 --> 00:16:04.110
Now this person, I think
is a plumber, right?

00:16:04.110 --> 00:16:06.302
Are plumbers judged
by other plumbers?

00:16:06.302 --> 00:16:07.260
Or are they judged by--

00:16:10.529 --> 00:16:12.830
OK, they're judged by
other plumbers, no?

00:16:12.830 --> 00:16:14.071
No, they're judged by you.

00:16:14.071 --> 00:16:14.820
You're the client.

00:16:14.820 --> 00:16:15.750
OK, very good.

00:16:15.750 --> 00:16:20.030
So if you-- they may love you,
other plumbers, but that's it.

00:16:20.030 --> 00:16:22.320
So any business where
you have contact

00:16:22.320 --> 00:16:28.560
with reality in the form
of your client judging you,

00:16:28.560 --> 00:16:31.110
has fewer what I call
expert problem, which

00:16:31.110 --> 00:16:33.060
I outlined in "The Black Swan."

00:16:33.060 --> 00:16:36.225
And expert being-- I used to
call an expert an empty suit

00:16:36.225 --> 00:16:37.770
until I discovered
that a lot of them

00:16:37.770 --> 00:16:39.780
actually don't
wear suits anymore.

00:16:39.780 --> 00:16:41.610
Times have changed,
so I have to rename it

00:16:41.610 --> 00:16:46.490
to something else
that's not Lindy.

00:16:46.490 --> 00:16:49.530
So there are classes
of people, there's

00:16:49.530 --> 00:16:51.960
a tableau in "The Black Swan."

00:16:51.960 --> 00:16:54.330
So who's an expert?

00:16:54.330 --> 00:16:57.360
Weather forecasters,
they're experts.

00:16:57.360 --> 00:17:01.200
Climate, we don't know.

00:17:01.200 --> 00:17:02.040
All right?

00:17:02.040 --> 00:17:04.460
Accountants, they're experts.

00:17:04.460 --> 00:17:07.369
If they can add
and subtract, you

00:17:07.369 --> 00:17:09.430
can have the evidence
that they're pretty much--

00:17:09.430 --> 00:17:12.420
and follow the rules of
various accounting rules,

00:17:12.420 --> 00:17:14.970
so they're experts.

00:17:14.970 --> 00:17:19.349
How about financial economists?

00:17:19.349 --> 00:17:22.650
Not experts, OK?

00:17:22.650 --> 00:17:25.050
So you have-- and very simple.

00:17:25.050 --> 00:17:27.262
No contact with reality,
no feedback from reality.

00:17:27.262 --> 00:17:28.470
So that's "Skin in the Game."

00:17:28.470 --> 00:17:31.170
That's the epistemology
of "Skin in the Game."

00:17:31.170 --> 00:17:33.300
And you can apply it
to a lot of things.

00:17:33.300 --> 00:17:35.880
People in policy making,
they're not experts.

00:17:35.880 --> 00:17:39.920
Anything macro, it's much easier
to macro BS than micro BS.

00:17:39.920 --> 00:17:41.910
And that's the
motto of the book.

00:17:41.910 --> 00:17:44.370
So in macro BS, you
don't see the feedback.

00:17:44.370 --> 00:17:46.380
You know a dentist
will be an expert,

00:17:46.380 --> 00:17:49.655
but an epidemiologist
will not be an expert

00:17:49.655 --> 00:17:50.910
because there is no feedback.

00:17:50.910 --> 00:17:52.570
That's "Skin in the Game."

00:17:52.570 --> 00:17:57.030
And this is very simple
Darwinian survival.

00:17:57.030 --> 00:17:57.630
Simple.

00:17:57.630 --> 00:18:00.990
I mean it's not too complicated
that it's Darwinian survival.

00:18:00.990 --> 00:18:03.040
Because it's very simple.

00:18:03.040 --> 00:18:08.830
You have a selection
process, you survive.

00:18:08.830 --> 00:18:10.610
Like in nature,
you have fitness.

00:18:10.610 --> 00:18:12.700
So we have all of
these people who

00:18:12.700 --> 00:18:16.540
reject the idea of intelligent
design, which they interpret

00:18:16.540 --> 00:18:20.350
say, in a naive way, first
order way, not as a metaphor.

00:18:20.350 --> 00:18:23.080
But they want to
be-- like academics,

00:18:23.080 --> 00:18:26.540
they want no contact
with reality.

00:18:26.540 --> 00:18:28.649
They want just rationalism
to make things work.

00:18:28.649 --> 00:18:29.690
It doesn't work that way.

00:18:29.690 --> 00:18:33.280
I mean, you cannot believe in
God when it comes to academia

00:18:33.280 --> 00:18:34.750
but disbelieve in God outside.

00:18:34.750 --> 00:18:37.660
You have to be consistent.

00:18:37.660 --> 00:18:40.150
And this of course, you
remember this cartoon

00:18:40.150 --> 00:18:43.990
which violates my idea
of the pseudo expert.

00:18:43.990 --> 00:18:46.450
Because they say,
"These smug pilots

00:18:46.450 --> 00:18:49.600
have lost touch regular
passengers like us.

00:18:49.600 --> 00:18:51.580
Who think I should
fly the plane?"

00:18:51.580 --> 00:18:56.080
So the point is, what
we're observing is not

00:18:56.080 --> 00:18:58.070
a riot against experts.

00:18:58.070 --> 00:19:01.320
It's a riot against a
certain class of experts.

00:19:01.320 --> 00:19:04.360
I call those IYI,
Intellectual Yet Idiot,

00:19:04.360 --> 00:19:06.340
because of lack of
contact with reality.

00:19:06.340 --> 00:19:10.180
Anything, like academia doesn't
have contact with reality,

00:19:10.180 --> 00:19:11.950
collapses.

00:19:11.950 --> 00:19:15.940
Academics-- are you
judged by peers, Pasquale?

00:19:15.940 --> 00:19:16.600
Who judges you?

00:19:16.600 --> 00:19:18.349
You're not going to--
are we in the same--

00:19:18.349 --> 00:19:19.900
we're not in the
same department.

00:19:19.900 --> 00:19:22.750
Who judges you, your
peers, other academics?

00:19:22.750 --> 00:19:25.430
Well, there's an expert problem.

00:19:25.430 --> 00:19:28.120
So if you're not
judged by PNL, we say,

00:19:28.120 --> 00:19:31.960
or reality, or
something like that.

00:19:31.960 --> 00:19:34.160
So the pilot definitely
has to be an expert.

00:19:34.160 --> 00:19:35.650
And there's a very
simple reason.

00:19:35.650 --> 00:19:39.270
What happened to pilots
who were pseudo experts?

00:19:39.270 --> 00:19:40.190
AUDIENCE: We die.

00:19:40.190 --> 00:19:41.273
NASSIM TALEB: There we go.

00:19:41.273 --> 00:19:42.680
There we go.

00:19:42.680 --> 00:19:44.620
They died and their
passengers died.

00:19:44.620 --> 00:19:46.870
So basically, we
have Darwinian--

00:19:46.870 --> 00:19:50.626
it's called Darwinian, the
school athlete, survival

00:19:50.626 --> 00:19:51.250
of the fittest.

00:19:51.250 --> 00:19:56.800
Or survival of the non-experts.

00:19:56.800 --> 00:20:01.810
And then of course, you end
up having fields such as--

00:20:01.810 --> 00:20:03.560
this is the mind
of an economist.

00:20:03.560 --> 00:20:04.740
[LAUGHTER]

00:20:04.740 --> 00:20:07.670
That's a clarity of mind on
a good day of an economist.

00:20:07.670 --> 00:20:08.170
Why?

00:20:08.170 --> 00:20:09.950
Because there's no
contact with reality.

00:20:09.950 --> 00:20:11.750
You don't have to be consistent.

00:20:11.750 --> 00:20:13.505
So you can have the
Nobel Prize given--

00:20:16.030 --> 00:20:17.720
the pseudo Nobel in economics--

00:20:17.720 --> 00:20:21.050
given to two people
saying opposite things.

00:20:21.050 --> 00:20:23.750
You can't say-- I mean, you
can't do that in physics.

00:20:23.750 --> 00:20:26.840
We say, you throw the ball it
goes up, and then it goes down.

00:20:26.840 --> 00:20:29.180
Let's be hedged, let's
give the Nobel to both.

00:20:29.180 --> 00:20:33.380
Because the problem is, you
end up with a mind like this

00:20:33.380 --> 00:20:37.520
if you're judged by your
peers, not by experts.

00:20:37.520 --> 00:20:40.740
So now the concept of symmetry.

00:20:40.740 --> 00:20:45.680
So let me do the following.

00:20:45.680 --> 00:20:50.270
Before I get into Hammurabi,
let me describe Wall Street.

00:20:50.270 --> 00:20:53.010
Hopefully this will
have a pointer.

00:20:53.010 --> 00:20:54.070
No, no pointer.

00:20:54.070 --> 00:20:55.640
OK.

00:20:55.640 --> 00:20:58.840
So there's something
I call the Bob Rubin

00:20:58.840 --> 00:21:01.550
trade, the absence of symmetry.

00:21:01.550 --> 00:21:06.520
And again, "Skin in the Game"
is about certain classes

00:21:06.520 --> 00:21:07.030
of symmetry.

00:21:07.030 --> 00:21:09.034
And we're going to see
where the name comes from

00:21:09.034 --> 00:21:10.450
and the link to
the pseudo expert.

00:21:13.684 --> 00:21:17.980
The fellow was chairman--

00:21:17.980 --> 00:21:19.490
now to be called chairperson--

00:21:19.490 --> 00:21:23.060
of Citibank or Citicorp.

00:21:23.060 --> 00:21:26.594
Spent 10 years there and
he received $120 million

00:21:26.594 --> 00:21:27.260
in compensation.

00:21:29.770 --> 00:21:34.310
And when the crisis
happened 10 years ago--

00:21:34.310 --> 00:21:35.420
I don't know if you were--

00:21:35.420 --> 00:21:36.460
many of you were born.

00:21:36.460 --> 00:21:41.110
Many of you at least were
conscious of what was going on.

00:21:41.110 --> 00:21:45.440
So 10 years ago,
there was a crisis.

00:21:45.440 --> 00:21:48.800
And then he said,
"Some very unfortunate,

00:21:48.800 --> 00:21:54.030
highly unexpected event, often
called "Black Swan," for which

00:21:54.030 --> 00:21:56.990
we apologize profusely but we
are excused as nobody could

00:21:56.990 --> 00:22:00.120
predict these things happened."

00:22:00.120 --> 00:22:00.920
Very nice.

00:22:00.920 --> 00:22:05.570
He acknowledged that it
was a black swan, named

00:22:05.570 --> 00:22:10.280
after a very, very stubborn
author, but sometimes pleasant

00:22:10.280 --> 00:22:12.680
if you have coffee with him.

00:22:12.680 --> 00:22:16.930
But stubborn definitely
intellectually.

00:22:16.930 --> 00:22:19.630
All right, so what's
the problem there?

00:22:19.630 --> 00:22:21.650
Let's think about it.

00:22:21.650 --> 00:22:25.320
You make the upside
when you're right.

00:22:25.320 --> 00:22:29.344
And when you're wrong,
who pays for the losses?

00:22:29.344 --> 00:22:30.220
Sorry?

00:22:30.220 --> 00:22:31.020
AUDIENCE: We did.

00:22:31.020 --> 00:22:32.110
NASSIM TALEB: You did.

00:22:32.110 --> 00:22:34.420
The Spanish grammar
instructors--

00:22:34.420 --> 00:22:36.020
a recurring person
in the book who

00:22:36.020 --> 00:22:40.190
pays for losses made by others--

00:22:40.190 --> 00:22:47.810
yoga instructors,
Google sushi chefs,

00:22:47.810 --> 00:22:51.210
and so on, they paid the
price directly or indirectly.

00:22:51.210 --> 00:22:55.130
So what we have
here is a violation

00:22:55.130 --> 00:22:59.000
of a law that effectively
is the first law

00:22:59.000 --> 00:23:02.570
extant, Hammurabi's rule.

00:23:02.570 --> 00:23:08.004
And it says the following,
if the architect

00:23:08.004 --> 00:23:09.420
builds a building
and the building

00:23:09.420 --> 00:23:13.200
collapses and kills the
owner of the building, what

00:23:13.200 --> 00:23:16.070
should happen to the architect?

00:23:16.070 --> 00:23:17.670
He should be put to death.

00:23:17.670 --> 00:23:21.630
I mean, it was Babylon 3,800
years ago, so they were not--

00:23:21.630 --> 00:23:23.790
didn't have a very
sophisticated legal code.

00:23:26.630 --> 00:23:32.120
And then of course, if
it kills the first born,

00:23:32.120 --> 00:23:35.070
the first born son of the
architect is put to death.

00:23:35.070 --> 00:23:38.020
So they're really, they're
looking for symmetry.

00:23:38.020 --> 00:23:40.910
Now what was the idea
of Hammurabi's code?

00:23:40.910 --> 00:23:46.370
It was not eye for eye, eye for
eye limiting damages and making

00:23:46.370 --> 00:23:48.080
things balanced, no.

00:23:48.080 --> 00:23:51.170
It was that you cannot walk
away from risks you've created

00:23:51.170 --> 00:23:52.870
for others.

00:23:52.870 --> 00:23:55.580
You should own your risks.

00:23:55.580 --> 00:23:58.200
That's the idea of
Hammurabi's code.

00:23:58.200 --> 00:24:01.360
You cannot have civilized
society unless those who create

00:24:01.360 --> 00:24:05.000
risks aren't also
aware of the risk.

00:24:05.000 --> 00:24:10.980
So when you get on a
highway, on the Hudson,

00:24:10.980 --> 00:24:13.710
you can get drunk,
whatever is something

00:24:13.710 --> 00:24:16.680
that people do when they
want to have fun or want

00:24:16.680 --> 00:24:19.859
to become reckless drivers,
and become a reckless driver.

00:24:19.859 --> 00:24:21.900
The best way if you want
to kill a lot of people,

00:24:21.900 --> 00:24:22.983
is you go against traffic.

00:24:26.540 --> 00:24:30.190
150 miles an hour
against traffic.

00:24:30.190 --> 00:24:34.774
Why is it that we don't see, we
don't hear about these people?

00:24:34.774 --> 00:24:36.440
AUDIENCE: Highly
symmetrical punishment.

00:24:36.440 --> 00:24:38.760
NASSIM TALEB: It's a highly
symmetrical punishment,

00:24:38.760 --> 00:24:41.380
they're already dead.

00:24:41.380 --> 00:24:45.120
Visibly, if you have these
traits, you're more exposed--

00:24:45.120 --> 00:24:48.440
you're exposed or even more
exposed than regular people.

00:24:48.440 --> 00:24:52.550
So at all times
in history, we've

00:24:52.550 --> 00:24:55.340
had that symmetry prevailing.

00:24:58.150 --> 00:25:00.340
We can look at it
operational symmetry.

00:25:00.340 --> 00:25:02.740
But let's first look at it
from a moral standpoint.

00:25:05.470 --> 00:25:08.080
You've heard of the
golden rule, do unto

00:25:08.080 --> 00:25:10.680
others what you want
them to do to you.

00:25:10.680 --> 00:25:15.370
Which I, in fact, I
find a little intrusive.

00:25:15.370 --> 00:25:18.910
Because say I like raw Lebanese
meat, Lebanese could be--

00:25:18.910 --> 00:25:20.960
I'm not going to
force you to eat it.

00:25:20.960 --> 00:25:24.280
So there's actually--
say I'm a bureaucrat

00:25:24.280 --> 00:25:26.830
and like this kind of
stuff, I'm don't force you.

00:25:26.830 --> 00:25:29.320
There is a much more
robust silver rule,

00:25:29.320 --> 00:25:32.120
don't do to others what you
don't want them to do to you.

00:25:32.120 --> 00:25:35.140
And effectively, you
can't have civilization

00:25:35.140 --> 00:25:37.060
without the silver rule.

00:25:39.580 --> 00:25:42.280
And also, and
unfortunately, people

00:25:42.280 --> 00:25:45.720
don't understand, it extends
to international affairs,

00:25:45.720 --> 00:25:47.110
the silver rule.

00:25:47.110 --> 00:25:47.740
How?

00:25:47.740 --> 00:25:49.750
Treat other
